Exactly.<p>ls example in zsh:<p><pre><code>  alias ls=&quot;ls -lph1 --color=always&quot;

  function ls {
    /bin/ls $@ | colout [regex] colours
  }
</code></pre>
This will pass all arguments after &quot;ls&quot; to the /bin/ls command. This also means you can keep your existing aliases clean and tidy for common params.<p>Remember to use the full path (or /usr/bin/env maybe) so that you don&#x27;t create a recursive call to your function ;)<p>This doesn&#x27;t deal with the situation of being unable to get the return value of the original command, but depending on your needs, this may not be an issue.<p>(edited for spacing)
